@NODE "Patterns" "Patterns (dir)"
@NEXT "Require"
@PREV "Intro"
@TOC "Intro"

@{CODE}@{JCENTER}@{APEN 2}Patterns (dir)

@{JLEFT}@{APEN 1}@{BODY}The Patterns drawer should contain the following (as well, some files may have
associated icons):
@{PAR}@{CODE}
@{" Skulls.iff " SYSTEM "SYS:Utilities/MultiView Patterns/Skulls.iff"}
@{" Stars.iff " SYSTEM "SYS:Utilities/MultiView Patterns/Stars.iff"}
@{" VienedMarble.iff " SYSTEM "SYS:Utilities/MultiView Patterns/VienedMarble.iff"}

Skulls conforms to the standard MWB8 palette set. However, Stars and
VienedMarble are just nice repeating patterns with their own palettes, so you
will need a screen depth greater than 4 (ie more than 16 colors) - CyberGfx is
recommended.

@ENDNODE

@REMARK------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE "Require" "System Requirements"
@PREV "Intro"

@{CODE}@{JCENTER}@{APEN 2}System Requirements
@{JLEFT}@{APEN 1}
@{BODY}An Amiga with OS2.0+...that's it!
@{PAR}
@{PAR}@{CODE}@{JCENTER}@{APEN 2}Suggested System
@{JLEFT}@{APEN 1}
@{BODY}An Amiga with OS3.1+ and a graphic board (using CyberGfx).
@{PAR}
@{PAR}@{B}NOTE:@{UB} OS1.X users may use MagicWB1.3 by Cléo Saulnier - available on aminet.

@ENDNODE

@REMARK------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE "Install" "Installation"

@{CODE}@{JCENTER}@{APEN 2}Installation
@{JLEFT}@{APEN 1}
@{BODY}You may need to modify the enclosed goods slightly to adapt them to your
environment (anything that I am currently aware of is explained within...feel
free to let @{"me" LINK "Author"} know of anything I left out).
@{PAR}
@{PAR}The contents of the original archive are listed in the @{"Introduction" LINK "Intro"}, along with
appropriate instructions.
@{PAR}
@{PAR}The way in which I use the included patterns is to randomize them with
@{"MagicSelector" LINK "MS"} which is now @{I}freeware!@{UI} You may, however, preform the same thing
by saving a preset for each picture (and window pattern), and then simply use
WBPattern in conjunction with a random file selector such as @{"FilePick" LINK "FP"}. For
example you could put the following line in your (User)Startup(-Sequence).
@{PAR}
@{PAR}@{APEN 3}  Prefs:WBPattern `C:FilePick Prefs:Presets/Pattern/#?.pre` USE@{APEN 1}
@{PAR}
@{PAR}This simply tells WBPattern to load and @{B}USE@{UB} (ie. not save) a random preset
(where the path would reflect the appropriate destination on @{I}your@{UI} harddrive).
Please note that the @{"FilePick" LINK "FP"} command is within @{B}tilde quotes@{UB} (upper-left key on
your keyboard).
@{PAR}
@{PAR}@{B}NOTE:@{UB} OS2.X users - you'll have to use @{B}NickPrefs@{UB} (which you can get in the
MagicWorkBench archive) to display the backdrops, however, you can still
randomize them in the same manner as described above.
@{PAR}
@{PAR}@{B}NOTE:@{UB} 4000 and 1200 owners - you'll probably have to run the images
through DPaint or ADpro to remap the palette (the colors for the standard MWB
palette tend to vary slightly for AGA machines and since IPrefs does such a
shitty job at remapping, you will have to do it yourself and save them. As
always, if you need help doing this, just @{"drop me an email" LINK "Author"}).
@{PAR}
@{PAR}See also @{"About the MWB16 Icons" LINK "16Icons"}.

@ENDNODE

@REMARK------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE "Interest" "For your interest..."

@{CODE}@{JCENTER}@{APEN 2}For your interest...

@{JLEFT}@{APEN 1}@{BODY}The following material was created on @{"my system" LINK "Author"} with an CyberVision64 Board
(Phase 5), PPaint (Cloanto), Art Department Professional (Elastic Reality), and
Iconian by @{"Chad Randall" LINK "Thanks"} (available on aminet).
@{PAR}
@{PAR}If you have the desire to create your own backgrounds and icons (which I
strongly encourage, so that I don't have to work so hard ;), here's what I do:
@{PAR}
@{PAR}@{CODE}@{JCENTER}@{APEN 2}The Color BackDrops

@{JLEFT}@{APEN 1}@{BODY}First I find a pic I like <g>, scan it (if it isn't already an image), then
load it into ADPro with the workbench palette locked (assuming you are already
running @{"the proper palette" LINK "16Icons"} (or you could load the palette from the
@{"MWB16Icons Template" SYSTEM "SYS:Utilities/MultiView Misc/MWB16Icons"}). You should run the image through ADPro TWICE!: once with
Floyd dithering (or the algorithm of your choice) on, and then a second pass
with it off. The reason for the two passes is because some parts of the pic will
look good dithered, and others won't, so I pick pieces out of each to make the
final image.  If you do not have ADPro...THEN BUY IT...well, you can remap the
image with the MWB palette right in PPaint (DPaint, etc.)...experiment for
yourself...
@{PAR}
@{PAR}The last step is the most time consuming. You will need to spend a lot of time
fixing the image up (hand antialiasing, dithering...) in order to make it look
nice . One tip: sometimes it's easiest to just trace the outline of the pic in
PPaint and then use the stencil to wipe out the rest of the image.  Now it's
just like a paint by number! Use the ranges tool to get the nice dithering
effects.  The magic wand tool in programs such as OpalPaint also help to get
rid of a lot of colors which are similar (thereby allowing you to reduce the
palette).
@{PAR}
@{PAR}Also I've discovered that darkening the palette (especially the pinks and
browns) will allow you to render some nice looking images with better better
results on skin tones - you may need to mess with the colors a few times before
you get the desired look. Next, simply load the image into PPaint and load the
orginal palette back in (do not remap!). Finally you will need to anti-alias
the image for best results.
@{PAR}@{PAR}
@{B}NOTE:@{UB} The dithering and anti-aliasing can make all the difference in the
world. Although, you have to develop a knack for it and it is very tedious and
time consuming, it makes the image look 100% better (IMO).
@{PAR}
@{PAR}@{CODE}@{JCENTER}@{APEN 2}The Grey-Scale Backgrounds

@{JLEFT}@{APEN 1}@{BODY}To make your own grey-scale images, just load your favorite picture into ADPro.
Run the Color-To-Grey operator. Set your screen-mode to whatever your workbench
is and a 4 color palette (make sure that dithering is envoked - Floyd works
well, and that the palette is sorted from Lightest to Darkest - this option is
in the Palette Requester in the Display Menu). Now render the screen. Edit the
palette (in the Display menu) as follows: copy the fourth color to the third
and then adjust the second color so that it is about midway between color 1 and
color 3 (which is the same as 4). So you now have a three color palette. Render
the image again.
@{PAR}
@{PAR}Now load the image into PPaint (or whatever) and remap the palette to the 3
grey colors of the MWB palette (you will need to swap the background grey with
the second color to remap (since in ADPro we picked sort from lightest to
darkest) and then swap them back and remap again). That's it, or...
@{PAR}
@{PAR}Sorry if this sounds confusing, but it @{I}IS@{UI} quite tedious. Feel free to drop @{"me" LINK "Author"} a
line if you get stuck or can't uderstand what I've tried to explain here. Also,
I would appreciate it VERY much if you would send me any pictures you make!
@{PAR}
@{PAR}GOOD LUCK!!

@ENDNODE

@REMARK------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE "16Icons" "About the MWB16 Icons"

@{CODE}@{JCENTER}@{APEN 2}About the MWB16 Icons
@{APEN 1}@{JLEFT}
@{BODY}These 16 colour icons were created using ADPro (Elastic Reality), PPaint
(Cloanto) and Iconian (Chad Randall - aminet:util/wb). With a 16 colour WB and
the right tools it is really easy to create nice looking icons!
@{PAR}
@{PAR}The icons in @{"16_Color (dir)" LINK "Icons2" 5} follow the standards proposed by @{"Roman Patzner" LINK "Card"} and
@{"R.E.Spence" LINK "Thanks"}. This also implies that the icons were designed to be used without
the default borders which OS2.0+ adds. To remove the borders you must have one
of the following (there may be others): @{B}MCP1.20+@{UB} (ALiEN DESiGN - available from
@{APEN 3}http://www.cs.tu-berlin.de/~zerocom/aliendesign.html@{APEN 1}), @{B}NoFillNoDraw.lha@{UB} (Kamel
Biskri (@{APEN 3}kbiskri@pratique.fr@{APEN 1}) - @{APEN 3}aminet/util/wb@{APEN 1}), or @{"Directory Opus 5.5" LINK "DOpus"} (Jonathon
Potter & GPSoftware - @{APEN 3}http://www.livewire.com.au/gpsoft/dopus55.html@{APEN 1}).
@{PAR}@{CODE}
@{APEN 2}To install 16 colour palette on your system:@{APEN 1}

  1. Change your screenmode to 16 colors.
  2. Load the User-Startup into your editor and change the MagicWB-Demon to:
     @{APEN 3}Run >NIL: C:MagicWB-Demon 4,123,123,123 5,175,175,175 6,170,144,124 7,255,169,151 8,80,80,80 9,40,62,91 10,96,128,96 11,226,209,119 12,255,212,203 13,122,96,72 14,210,210,210 15,229,93,93 @{APEN 1}
     (This line is provided in the @{" S (dir) " LINK "S"} of this archive).
  3. Do the same with your Startup-Sequence (if required).
  4. Load Prefs/Palette and change the last four colours to
            255,212,203   122,96,72   210,210,210   229,93,93
     and save it. After re-boot everything should work fine.

The colors below should match with their description if you've succeeded:

  0.     Background  -> 149,149,149     8. @{BPEN 8}  @{BPEN 0}  Darkgrey    ->  80, 80, 80
  1. @{BPEN 1}  @{BPEN 0}  Black       ->   0,  0,  0     9. @{BPEN 9}  @{BPEN 0}  Antrahzit   ->  40, 62, 91
  2. @{BPEN 2}  @{BPEN 0}  White       -> 255,255,255    10. @{BPEN 10}  @{BPEN 0}  Green       ->  96,128, 96
  3. @{BPEN 3}  @{BPEN 0}  Blue        ->  59,103,162    11. @{BPEN 11}  @{BPEN 0}  Yellow      -> 226,209,119
  4. @{BPEN 4}  @{BPEN 0}  Med.grey    -> 123,123,123    12  @{BPEN 12}  @{BPEN 0}  Brightrose  -> 255,212,203
  5. @{BPEN 5}  @{BPEN 0}  BrightgreyI -> 175,175,175    13. @{BPEN 13}  @{BPEN 0}  Brown       -> 122, 96, 72
  6. @{BPEN 6}  @{BPEN 0}  Brightbrown -> 170,144,124    14. @{BPEN 14}  @{BPEN 0}  Brightgrey  -> 210,210,210
  7. @{BPEN 7}  @{BPEN 0}  Rose        -> 255,169,151    15. @{BPEN 15}  @{BPEN 0}  Red         -> 229, 93, 93

  @{B}Note@{UB}: @{"MUI" LINK "MUI"} applications look strange without rearranging the colors.

@{APEN 2}To simply test this or see what it will look like:@{APEN 1}

  1. Open the @{" P&C " LINK "P&C"} drawer of this archive.
  2. Click on @{B}ClickMeFirst@{UB}.
  3. Click on @{B}ClickForColors16@{UB}.
  4. Click on @{B}ClickForScreen@{UB} and slide the Colors slider to 16 and hit @{B}USE@{UB}.

  To get everything back to normal just follow steps 3 & 4 for 8 colors
  instead of 16.

@ENDNODE

