@NODE "MWB" "About MagicWB v2.0"
@NEXT "MWB"
@PREV "MWB"

@{CODE}@{JCENTER}@{APEN 2}MagicWB v2.0

@{JLEFT}@{APEN 1}@{BODY}The definitive WB-Enhancer no Amiga can do without. MagicWB is a full
replacement for the graphic user interface of the Workbench and has become
the standard on the Amiga.
@{PAR}
@{PAR}MagicWB 2.0 is completely restructured on a new color-allocation scheme which
more than doubles the speed of the WB and reduces chip-consumption to only a
third compared with all previous versions and also features a highly improved
color palette. MWB 2.0 introduces a never-before-seen standard for over four
dozen of new image-drawers to achieve a more diversified look on your WB.
More icons, dock-brushes, a dozen of new patterns, fonts and a AA-support
complete this special product.
@{PAR}
@{PAR}The demo-version can be found on Aminet biz/demo/MagicWB20d.lha.
@{PAR}
@{PAR}@{CODE}@{JCENTER}MagicWB is © by Martin Huttenloher.

@ENDNODE


@NODE "MS" "MagicSelector"
@NEXT "MS"
@PREV "MS"

@{CODE}@{JCENTER}@{APEN 2}MagicSelector by 0yvind Falch, Triumph Software

@{JLEFT}@{APEN 1}@{BODY}I installed MagicWorkbench (by Martin Huttenloher) and after a while I wanted
to have a different background and sound for Workbench each time I booted my
Amiga. So, I wrote two programs to help me select a background and a sound for
each startup. These programs are:
@{PAR}
@{PAR}MagicSelector Preferences
@{PAR}MagicSelector Main
@{PAR}
@{PAR}I had to make MagicSelector Preferences, so the user can specify the files
(s)he wants to use for Workbench. MagicSelector Main is the WBStartup program
which sets up your background(s) and sound. I have also included some
background patterns and sounds with the archive.
@{PAR}
@{PAR}MagicSelector software and documentation are © 1994-1995 by Řyvind Falch,
Triumph Software. All rights reserved. MagicSelector Preferences and
MagicSelector Main is written in assembler using Devpack 3.04 and MUI Assembler
include files by Henri Veisterä.
@{PAR}
@{PAR}AND, MagicSelector is now FREEWARE, thanx to its registered users!
@{PAR}@{CODE}
0yvind Falch
Triumph Software
Norderhovgata 26
0654 Oslo
Norway

@{APEN 3}Email:@{APEN 1}    oef@netcom-gsm.no
@{APEN 3}Voice:@{APEN 1}    +47 33 04 47 13
@{APEN 3}Mobile:@{APEN 1}   928 68060           (Cool Mobile number :-))

@ENDNODE


@NODE "MUI" "MUI - MagicUserInterface © Copyright 1992-95 by Stefan Stuntz"
@NEXT "MUI"
@PREV "MUI"

@{CODE}@{JCENTER}@{APEN 2}MUI - MagicUserInterface © Copyright 1992-95 by Stefan Stuntz
@{JLEFT}@{APEN 1}
@{BODY}MagicUserInterface (also known as MUI) is a complete system to create and
maintain graphical user interfaces.
@{PAR}
@{PAR}The central scheme behind MUI assumes that only the user (and not the
programmer) of an application knows how the program (s)he is using best fits
his/her personal needs, and that of his/her computer system.  Because MUI
applications don't contain any absolute values for sizes or positions, the
programmer instead only defines objects and groups of objects. Such objects
are defined on run time by MUI according to the users settings.
@{PAR}
@{PAR}Consequently, an MUI application gives the user *many* more important
advantages:
@{PAR}@{CODE}
 · Font sensitivity
 · Changeable window sizes
 · Flexibility
 · Controlling by keyboard
 · System integration
 · Adjusting to its environment

@{BODY}All of the MUI settings listed above (and more) can be changed by the user via
the MUI preferences program.  This can be set for every program in one setting
(global) or can be set for each and every single application.
@{PAR}
@{PAR}Available on Aminet (dev/gui) - @{B}Get it!@{UB}

@ENDNODE


